  <h2>Bootstrap Build — What Changes</h2>
  <p>Get the shell livable for ~$33k, then upgrade over time. The house is designed to be source-agnostic (grid/solar) and every system can be upgraded in place.</p>

  <h3>Deferred to later</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Solar + battery ($8,600–11,100):</strong> use grid power via 50A inlet. Add solar when budget allows — Sol-Ark and wiring are designed for this</li>
    <li><strong>Minisplit ($1,200–2,000):</strong> woodstove for heat, box fans for summer. Add minisplit when ready</li>
    <li><strong>W/D combo ($1,500–1,800):</strong> laundromat until settled. Plumbing roughed in for later install</li>
    <li><strong>DishDrawer ($1,000–1,100):</strong> hand wash. Cabinet space ready for later</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cheaper alternatives</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Windows:</strong> reclaimed from salvage yards / Habitat ReStore ($25–100 each vs $300–500). DIY fixed windows from tempered glass panels. Skip Velux skylights, use Sun Tunnels (~$200 each) or cheaper fixed skylights</li>
    <li><strong>Composting toilet:</strong> Nature's Head (~$1,000) or DIY bucket system ($200–500) instead of Clivus Multrum ($2–3k)</li>
    <li><strong>Fridge:</strong> basic compact (Danby, Magic Chef, $300–500) instead of IKEA SUPERKALL ($900)</li>
    <li><strong>Interior finishes:</strong> plywood or luan panel ceilings ($0.50–0.80/sf) instead of full shiplap — lightweight and handles trailer flex (drywall cracks when towed). Stained plywood subfloor ($50–100, already there) or vinyl plank ($1–2/sf) instead of hardwood. Skip bathroom tile, use FRP panels (~$100)</li>
    <li><strong>Electrical:</strong> skip smart load management panel ($500–800), just manage loads manually</li>
    <li><strong>Rainwater:</strong> IBC totes ($50–100 for 275 gal) instead of purpose-built tank. Simplify to 3-stage filtration</li>
    <li><strong>Plumbing fixtures:</strong> standard chrome instead of brass. Saves $100–200</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Don't cut these</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Trailer:</strong> the foundation. No place to cheap out</li>
    <li><strong>Insulation + air sealing:</strong> envelope performance pays for itself in energy costs. Comfortboard option is already the budget path</li>
    <li><strong>Metal roof:</strong> needed for rainwater catchment and longevity</li>
    <li><strong>Woodstove:</strong> primary heat + backup cooking. Worth the $1,600</li>
  </ul>

